## Quickstart

```bash
uv sync            # install dependencies
uv run [[ package_name ]]    # start the server ([[ transport ]])
uv run pytest      # run the tests
```

[% if http %]
The server speaks **Streamable HTTP** and listens on `http://127.0.0.1:8000/mcp/`
by default. Configure host/port/transport via environment variables (see
[`.env.example`](./.env.example)).
[% else %]
The server speaks **stdio**, which is what local clients like Claude Desktop and
Cursor expect. Switch to HTTP any time by setting `MCP_TRANSPORT=http` (see
[`.env.example`](./.env.example)).
[% endif %]

## Connect a client

### MCP Inspector

```bash
npx @modelcontextprotocol/inspector uv run [[ package_name ]]
```

### Claude Desktop / Cursor

Add this to your client's MCP config:

```json
{
  "mcpServers": {
    "[[ package_name ]]": {
      "command": "uv",
      "args": ["run", "[[ package_name ]]"],
      "cwd": "/absolute/path/to/[[ project_name ]]"
    }
  }
}
```
[% if auth_enabled %]

## Authentication

This server is an **OAuth 2.1 resource server**. It validates JWT access tokens
issued by an external Authorization Server and exposes the discovery metadata
MCP clients need:

- `GET /.well-known/oauth-protected-resource` — [RFC 9728](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/html/rfc9728)
  Protected Resource Metadata advertising your trusted authorization server(s).
- Unauthenticated requests receive `401` with a `WWW-Authenticate` challenge
  that points clients at the metadata, so they can discover and complete the
  OAuth flow automatically.

Token validation (signature, issuer, audience, expiry) is configured in
[`src/[[ package_name ]]/auth.py`](./src/[[ package_name ]]/auth.py) via FastMCP's
`RemoteAuthProvider` + `JWTVerifier`. Set the `MCP_OAUTH_*` variables in `.env`
to your provider — for example [Keycloak](https://www.keycloak.org),
[WorkOS AuthKit](https://www.authkit.com), [Auth0](https://auth0.com) or
Microsoft Entra ID. The scaffold ships the *resource* server; the authorization
server is whichever IdP you point it at.
[% endif %]

## Docker

```bash
docker build -t [[ project_name ]] .
docker run -p 8000:8000 [[ project_name ]]
```

## Project structure

```
[[ project_name ]]/
├── src/[[ package_name ]]/
│   ├── server.py      # the FastMCP instance (+ /health route[% if auth_enabled %] + auth[% endif %])
│   ├── tools.py       # your tools, resources and prompts
│   ├── settings.py    # typed configuration (pydantic-settings)
│   ├── app.py         # FastAPI host that mounts MCP at /mcp
[% if auth_enabled %]│   ├── auth.py        # OAuth 2.1 resource-server wiring
[% endif %]│   └── __main__.py    # `uv run [[ package_name ]]` entrypoint
├── tests/             # in-memory tests — no network required
├── Dockerfile
└── .github/workflows/ci.yml
```

## Adding tools

Open `src/[[ package_name ]]/tools.py` and add a typed function:

```python
@mcp.tool
def greet(name: str) -> str:
    """Say hello."""
    return f"Hello, {name}!"
```

Types become the tool's input schema automatically. Return a `pydantic` model
for structured output. See the [FastMCP docs](https://gofastmcp.com/servers/tools).

## Running alongside an existing API

[`app.py`](./src/[[ package_name ]]/app.py) mounts the MCP server inside a FastAPI
app, so you can serve your own REST routes next to it:

```bash
uv run uvicorn [[ package_name ]].app:api --host 0.0.0.0 --port 8000
```

